    <item>
      <title>Push a Git repo to multiple remotes with unique SSH keys</title>
      <link>http://localhost:1313/posts/git-repo-multiple-remotes-ssh/</link>
      <pubDate>Wed, 22 Feb 2023 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>http://localhost:1313/posts/git-repo-multiple-remotes-ssh/</guid>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;For one reason or another, you might like to push a Git repo to more than one remote. This website automatically gets pushed to both &lt;a href=&#34;https://codeberg.org/gomarcd/gomarcd-website&#34;&gt;Codeberg&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href=&#34;https://github.com/gomarcd/gomarcd-website&#34;&gt;Github&lt;/a&gt;, for example.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;Here, I will discuss how I&amp;rsquo;ve set things up.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;h2 id=&#34;managing-multiple-ssh-keys&#34;&gt;Managing multiple SSH keys&lt;/h2&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;With &lt;a href=&#34;https://www.oreilly.com/library/view/ssh-the-secure/0596008953/ch01s01.html&#34;&gt;SSH&lt;/a&gt;, you can securely push changes to your Git remotes without needing to enter login credentials every time. For a single repository, there is minimal setup: just upload your public key.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
